The fungal results came back negative😄. Now we can start treatment for EGC. His medication is on its way to his foster mom. I’m thrilled because this means he no longer has to be kept away from other cats and kittens because now we know it’s not contagious. This is such good news. I don’t know when he will be coming here but I’m hoping he and Cleo hit it off. 
Yesterday was #GivingTuesday2022 and we raised a little over $3,300 across platforms. Thank you to everyone who shared or donated. Your donations help kittens like Pinocchio who would’ve otherwise been euthanized. You’re the best. I’m leaving the fundraiser up for a few days in the hopes we can reach our goal. What can I say.. I’m an optimist😄

Whiskey here with your daily dose of floof😸.
This sweet boy is the last of the liquor kittens looking for a home. Do you have room in your heart for some extra fluff?

Someone get Whiskey some mittens before he freezes his paws off 🥶

Troll Control: Whiskey was out like a light and was either unaware of or just did not mind sporting this adorable little getup while I took a few pics. I think we can all agree he looks adorable☺️
Polar is enjoying the free belly massage. You’d think he was their mom by the way he lets them climb all over him.

Pinocchio has an appointment with a dermatologist on the 20th. Hopefully we can have allergy testing done to pinpoint what we need to avoid in order to keep the eosinophilic plaques under control. I’m stoked to watch him heal and learn more about this condition.

If anyone has a dolphin who can translate I would love to know what he’s saying. 

Amaretto, Brandy, Whiskey, and Bourbon are getting spayed and neutered today😄. I just dropped them off. I’m sure Cleo is going to enjoy having some peace and quiet😝

I don’t know what’s in those pain meds but Brandy is feelin good! All four kittens were altered today and are back home acting like nothing happened. Except for Brandy who suddenly has it out for the hand vacuum.

Many thanks to everyone who has followed along and shown support for my fostering efforts. The next adventure begins. In the beginning of January I’m going to hopefully trap the mom of the floofs and the other ferals on the property. This is new territory for me but I’m stoked.

Sorry @peta but they WILL be returned to the place they call home😊

Caption this

Tomorrow is going to be eventful. I’m dropping off the traps so the caregivers can start getting the cats used to them and Pinocchio is being dropped off here😄

Pinocchio’s nose appears to be healing slowly. What do you think? He slept on my pillow last night and the others are warming up to him🙂

#EosinophilicGranulomaComplexCat
There were only so many transformation photos I could fit!

Update 3:20pm: Pinocchio tested negative for FIV and FeLV. PHEW

Original post 11am: Pinocchio has settled in nicely. He’s currently on antibiotics for a URI. You can hear his noisy breathing in this video. I’m making sure to take plenty of photos of his lesion so I can best understand how it is responding or not responding to his current treatment plan. His appointment with the dermatologist yesterday went well and the vet has another suspicion on what the cause might be. For now he is off the steroids. I’ll be in touch with the dermatologist if it starts looking worse or gets bigger. Vet appointments, especially with specialists, in my experience, can sometimes be disappointing. I’ve had enough experience with being dismissed to have guarded optimism when going to a new clinic. I’m extremely happy with the thoroughness of Dr. Plant @skinvetclinic. He answered all my questions, explained his reasoning for recommending another test and why I should stop giving Pinocchio steroids for the time being. He caught me just as I was about to drive away and gave me a print out with more information on the specific test, and the clinic sent a followup email asking how he’s doing and letting me know I can ask any questions about the current plan. I’ll share more info about his suspicions later today after we snap test Pinocchio.

Instagram wants us to use this template and audio to tell everyone how amazing 2022 was. I wasn’t about to turn down an easy $10 but I also won’t lie. This year was tough. I struggled to keep my anxiety under control and had one of the most difficult extended weekends of my life. I’ve heard of debilitating anxiety but had never had a panic attack last more than an hour max. 72 hours of back to back panic attacks and constant adrenaline was hell. It’s something that, unless you’ve experienced it, is impossible understand. After years of not wanting to try a SSRI I took the plunge out of pure desperation. I was also able to find an incredible therapist (highly recommend) after years of being stubborn. I guess sometimes we need to reach our breaking point before trying things we pushed against for so long. I share this with you all because I know I’m not alone and I don’t want anyone to feel that they are.

I have to share this small but incredible change. Pinocchio’s lesion is healing nicely and the healed area of skin (the area not circled in blue) is growing. Before starting steroids the entire area was a similar texture to the areas circled in blue. Even though the mark on his face looks big it’s looking so much better and it’s amazing to see the progress. #EosinophilicGranulomaComplexKitten

When I made this I had no idea it would get as many views as it did and I definitely did not expect the outpouring of love and support or for it to be one of my top 3 videos this year. I suppose it’s a testament to the power of vulnerability.

Original (shortened): This post is personal (maybe controversial) and I hope that’s okay. It does relate to my fostering in a much larger way than I can explain. I was in a relationship with someone I trusted and loved who began constantly invalidating my feelings on everything. It was my fault for being sad when a foster passed because I chose to foster in the first place. Once, he even suggested I quit. Over time he chipped away at my self confidence all while telling me he loved me, wanted to have children and get a place together. So, as you can imagine, it was a huge shock to find out he had been carrying on a relationship with a man he’d been seeing since before we’d gotten together. I was essentially being used so he could keep up the façade of being a heterosexual man and he could have biological children (a boy, specifically) to “pass on his family bloodline.” His words. I know a conversation could be had about how some people are afraid to be their true selves and we should be empathetic. But the ramifications this had on me were significant and I t’s been a challenge to acknowledge that my feelings are valid. I’m proud of the progress I’ve made and although I still feel a twinge of “maybe he’s right” when I’m crying over a kitten I’m struggling to keep alive, I’m getting better at remembering who I was before I allowed him to destroy my peace. I hope everyone who is healing from any emotional wounds takes the time to acknowledge the progress they’ve made even if it’s small. It’s still significant and you should be proud. I am.

This was Flower. She had infections behind her sealed eyelids and I needed to open them to drain the pus. Her eyes healed beautifully❤️

Marionberry was finally well enough to not need supplemental oxygen and to meet uncle Polar who was curious about what I’d been hiding from him in the bathroom.

With less than 10 minutes until 2023, I give you my top post of the year.
The bathtub was a temporary place for them while they adjusted to life inside and learned to use a litter box. Happy New Year, friends!! Here’s to 2023 and more kittens 🥂 🎉

This morning I completed my very first release. Massive thank you to everyone on patreon for making this possible. Your help is invaluable. The three cats we trapped a couple days ago were all males and now they won’t be contributing to the overpopulation and needless suffering of kittens they could have fathered. Trappers have always had my respect but dang that was a lot of work. The driving alone was four hours and 168 miles. Unfortunately we didn’t get the three others and are waiting for the next appointments to get them altered. Please consider joining my patreon (link in bio) to help make this possible. Embarrassingly I need to ask for help. Continuing won’t be sustainable. So many people had said they would be part of patreon and a small percentage followed through. I’m doing my best to keep going but I need your help.

The only time I can get a decent shot of Pinocchio’s nose is when he is zonked out. I took this two weeks ago. The lesion has changed a bit within the past two weeks. We got the immunohistochemistry (don’t ask me to say that out loud because I will embarrass myself) results back which confirmed the lesion is not feline herpesvirus related.

😆
But for real.

This sweet girl will never be used for profit again. She’s a f4 Savannah which means one of her great great grandparents was a Serval. Owning a f4 Savannah is illegal in Georgia, Hawaii, Nebraska, New York, Rhode Island, and most counties in Texas. Delaware requires a permit. She was being sold intact and possibly pregnant by a family who is closing their cattery. We do not believe she is pregnant and if she is she is very likely in the early stages. She is going to be spayed and hopefully she will feel safe soon and we can start searching for her perfect family. @theswiftiekittens currently has her with some kittens to try and bring her out of her shell. She had a name but we’re not keeping it. New life, new name. Leave suggestions. I’m thinking of Prim.
Look who is settling in nicely🥰. @theswiftiekittens sent me some video updates of this sweet girl.
Sweet dreams

The official count is 29 toes. Cats typically have 10 front toes so between the four of them there should be 40. I love them already. They’re currently napping and getting settled in. The most severely affected has one toe on one paw and two on the other. There are two claws coming from the one toe. I’m letting them relax for a bit before I get a better look. It’s been a big day for them.

#TheBeanieBabyKittens

First things first. Names. We are going with bean names to make up for their missing digits. I’m kind of in love with Garbanzo. They don’t need to be actual beans (coffee beans count) so leave your cute bean names below. There are four males. One has a normal amount of toes. The other three are missing some. As to not make the one kitten feel excluded he will also be given a bean name. 

Okay, now the second and least important part of the agenda: vet care😜. This little guy has some truly odd feet. The other paw has a dewclaw that’s done a 360 and looks like a snail shell. My guess is that will have to come off. The paw in the photo has two nails growing from the same spot. I’m not sure how to best manage this. The last kitten I had with two claws coming from the same spot developed a super claw. The two claws fused and trimming it was not advised. Since it would eventually curl into her skin we had it removed. Fortunately it was where her dewclaw was so it wasn’t a huge deal. I’m bringing this guy to @guardianvetcare tomorrow and will keep everyone updated. At the moment he is getting around really well and is the bravest of the bunch.

#TheBeanieBabyKittens

Introducing Pinto. He’s sporting eight front beans but he’s still a 10 if you ask me.

#TheBeanieBabyKittens
Pinto and I share several things in common with distractibility being one of them. Focusing is a skill we’re both

Two of the beans aren’t feeling well:(. Can you tell which two? 
I’m going to try to get them in to the vet tomorrow. Poor things don’t want to eat and keep throwing up.
Fava is feeling a bit better after his meds which he very much dislikes

If your notes, homework, work papers don’t have evidence of cat hair, paw prints or chew marks on them, do you really own a cat? 
Fava (black with white locket) and Garbanzo (not in video) are doing much better. I haven’t decided on a name for the little guy with 3 front toes. Little Bean and Baby Bean are the two I’m stuck on. Help.

These are Baby Bean’s front feet. This condition is called syndactyly. The paw on the left has two fused toes resulting in two claws coming from one spot. He gets around easily but needs an adopter who will be able to keep an eye on him for any signs of discomfort so they can seek help from a vet. At this time we do not know how his little paws will affect him in the future but keeping him on the slender side is an absolute must. No free feeding or over feeding. The less weight on these paws the better.

I have Marionberry updates but no recent videos of her because she’s always on my lap. Still no diagnosis BUT we have ruled out so many things. The results of the biopsy sample taken from her esophagus are consistent with inflammation from acid reflux. She may have a sliding hiatal hernia, a rare diagnosis in cats, but not unheard of. It can be difficult to diagnose so we are scheduling a fluoroscopy appointment which will give us a definitive answer. I know it might sound ridiculous to be pursuing this and my only justification is that I want her to feel better. If she has a sliding hiatal hernia that can be repaired, I think we should give her that. 
Video of Polar and Pinocchio.
If you’ve made it this far let me know where you’re commenting from.
This cat and his fries😂. Doesn’t like cat treats. Loves fries and pieces of tortillas.
Just a mama and his babies

This is Pinocchio. Due to lack of resources at the shelter, he was in the process of being scheduled for euthanasia. They could not afford to pay for a biopsy to determine the cause of the lesion on his face. Thanks to social media and a great network of fosters and volunteers he was able to land safely here. Everyone who has donated to @shelbyskittensafehouse has helped us do the appropriate testing and get a diagnosis: eosinophilic granuloma complex (EGC). He’s being treated with steroids and his lesion is slowly but surely healing. Today there is a new patch of fresh skin that I feel is worth celebrating. 
At the moment we are in need of cat litter. If you would like to send us some the link is currently in my story❤️. 
#perfectlyimperfect #eosinophilicgranulomacomplexcat

The Bean Kittens were desexed today. Anyone want to take a wild guess about why Baby Bean’s belly is shaved and there’s an incision? I’ll like the comment(s) that guess correctly😄. 
Garbanzo is currently growling like a wild man and holding onto a toy. Pinto is going after the catnip plant I bought the other day. Fava has decided to take on the challenge of the bully stick I had gotten for Polar. Surgery days are entertaining😅

Update: if you guessed cryptorchidism you are correct! One of his testes hadn’t descended and @theswiftiekittens had to go searching for it.

Happy 1st birthday to the bestest girl!! When I first got Marionberry I took no time naming her because I wasn’t sure she would survive the night. I love this little cat with all my heart. She’s a fighter and hopefully by the end of April we’ll have her chronic acid reflux figured out 🤞🏽
Polar is the best foster dad❤️. He allows the bean kittens to climb all over him and dig through his fur hoping to nurse.

This sweet baby is thriving with his new mom and siblings. This video is from the night I had him. Fortunately, one of @theswiftiekittens pregnant cats gave birth overnight and he fit right in❤️. It brings me a lot of comfort knowing his colony is currently being TNR’d so no more kittens have to suffer.
Happy international cat lady day. I’m still processing Ashley’s passing. I know many of you are, as well. All we can do now is honor her wish for us to take care of each other.

We welcomed this cutie patootie last night. He’s been dewormed and treated for fleas and seems to be a healthy little guy. He has an umbilical hernia that’ll be fixed when he’s neutered. I’m still deciding on a name for him.

I love using syringes for a variety of reasons but one of them is to help feed kittens who’ve entered my home around this age who aren’t too keen on latching but not quite ready for just food. As I depress the plunger he eagerly laps the KMR. Once he is done he will typically move his head to the side and/or KMR will just start dripping from his mouth. He’s also eating a bit of raw food. I’m aware of the controversy surrounding raw food especially when it comes to kittens and their developing immune systems. However, I’ve found that kittens wean onto food better when it’s raw vs canned. Not only do they start eating it more readily but in my experience their digestive systems tend to do better with the introduction to raw evidenced by their good poops. We all love a good poo. The raw food I feed is premade and has all the nutrients cats need. 
I’ve added some things to my Amazon wish list that we could really use. The link is in my bio. We are also still raising funds for Marionberry’s upcoming surgery at Oregon State University. You can use the link on this post or PayPal: shelbyskittensafehouse@gmail.com

Also, check that little pee spot in the litter box!! He had zero accidents!

Baby Tango has been the most wonderful little house guest. I wish he had a buddy. Here are some updates.

Garbanzo was adopted on Tuesday😄. He has another young cat in the household to keep him company and hopefully keep him out of trouble😆. 

Pinocchio’s nose is looking better and better but still not quite completely healed. 

Marionberry is scheduled to have surgery at OSU on May 10. 

On Sunday I am picking up a friendly calico and her four newborns to bring into NWAC’s care.

Finally worked out dates to start trapping a new colony. 

I’ll be back to posting more on Sunday. I only dog-sit overnight for two families a few times a year and this past week was one of them. It’s been hectic. I know my posts have been few and far between but the work hasn’t stopped and I’m grateful for everyone who understands and continues to support this passion of mine.
You can see Tango’s umbilical hernia while he shows off some Shakira dance moves. He got to meet the other fosters. They have mixed reviews.

Tango is spicy. Check out Polar’s concerned face👀. This is how Tango lets me know he’s done playing and it’s time for a snack and a nap. Just like babies he can get a little cranky. Since Tango is still a little guy he sleeps in the bathtub with cozy blankets and a soft squishy bed. As you can see he is very up front when my services don’t meet his needs in a timely manner. He never tips so it’s a good thing he’s cute.

These three were found by a good samaritan who took them in. There had been four but one passed away last night. I brought them to @theswiftiekittens and one tested slight positive for panleukopenia so I took them to an ER for treatment. They will check their white blood cells and if any of them have ungodly low numbers we will let them pass peacefully. The little black one seems to have a fighting chance but the two grey and white ones surprised me a bit with their energy so who knows. Right now at the ER their names are Kitten 1, Kitten 2 and Kitten 3🙃. I didn’t have time to come up with names for them. We could really use some help covering their cost. The downpayment was $1500. Please help us give these little guys a chance. Panleuk is an awful virus. If they make it through the night @theswiftiekittens is going to get blood from a donor cat tomorrow for serum and I’ll pick it up and bring it to the ER clinic so they can treat the kittens with it. My PayPal is shelbyskittensafehouse@gmail.com and venmo is @fosterkittenlove. I will keep everyone updated on this post when I get updates from the vet❤️

Modified update #1: We’re giving them all a shot. One is worse than the other two but not so bad we feel euthanasia is our only option at this point.

Update #2: I just got a call from the clinic letting me know Kitten 3 is beyond saving. Kitten 3 is the one on the right in this photo. I wish I could have gotten to know him more. They were in my care for no more than two hours and I’m still so sad we were not able to save him.

Update #3: May 8 11:40am - Kitten 1 and Kitten 2 ate a little on their own this morning. Kitten 1 did not urinate all night which was a concern but he emptied his bladder with some assistance around 10am. They’re still very touch and go but I’m feeling more optimistic now that they’ve made it through the night.

Update #4: May 9 10:45am - Kitten 1 and Kitten 2 are continuing to improve and are no longer on IV fluids and medication. They’re tolerating their oral meds well and neither had any diarrhea last night.

You’d never know this adorable bundle of cuteness was a fierce paw throwing Puss in Boots impersonating fireball last night when it was time to get vaccinated.

It’s 10:45am and I haven’t heard from the vet about the two panleuk kittens. No news is good news but I’m guessing this means they will need to stay a bit longer. I will continue to post any and all updates on the post before this one.

Marionberry’s surgery on Wednesday went well. Before they started surgery they took X-rays to check for aspiration pneumonia. She has two small areas in one lung lobe but they weren’t concerning enough to prevent them from going ahead with the procedure. She stayed the night for observation so they could assess her pain management needs. Poor girl spiked a fever overnight and didn’t want to eat. I let them know she will devour churus so that’s what her meals consisted of😂. By noon her fever was down, she was using the litter box and they felt it was in her best interest to go home where she won’t be so stressed. I can’t believe how well she is handling everything. We had to change up our routine at home to accommodate her healing process. She can’t be running and wrestling with the others and since the panleuk babies are in my bathroom I can’t keep her in there. She has the run of the house and I think it’s safe to say she loves it. Thank you to everyone who made this life changing surgery possible.

#SlidingHiatalHerniaCat

Mentally prepared for any cruel comments🧘🏽‍♀️. The two panleuk kittens have been staying in the tub and are continuing to get better. Is it messy? Absolutely. Are they messy? 💯. Is the mess you see in this video just a fraction of how messy it can get? You bet. Panleukopenia is a terrible virus that takes the lives of many kittens and puts foster homes on lockdown. The virus can live for over a year in the environment and is highly contagious. The next time someone tells you they don’t vaccinate because (insert outrageous reason) please show them the first photo I posted of them and be sure to let them know a vaccine could have prevented the horrendous start my two survivors got. Sadly, two in their litter did not survive. I have to be extremely careful when exiting the bathroom to make sure I don’t introduce panleuk to the rest of the house. Hopefully I will get more pictures of them soon but I’m trying to not bring my phone in there too often. I’ve decided to name one of them Bodhi but I haven’t decided on which one. I love them both and can’t wait to be able to snuggle the snot out of them and let them meet Tango eventually.

Some clips of Satori getting a bath and a very *slight* overreaction to getting yuck water splashed on me. She is a little spitfire and I just know she and Tango will be besties. 
Satori and Bodhi (panleuk kittens) came along when I was still raising money for Marionberry’s sliding hiatal hernia surgery. They were hospitalized for two nights and I thought I had a good enough buffer in our bank account but I also *slightly* overestimated and we can really use help. Liking, sharing, commenting, donating are all ways to help. Panleuk is such a horrible virus and I deeply understand why some rescues and shelters opt for euthanasia rather than treatment at times. Many people do not want the virus in their homes at all (completely understandable) and the kittens can end up costing a lot of money. With mortality rates as high as they are, sometimes trying to save them is not an option from a logistical standpoint. @theswiftiekittens texted me asking if I wanted some 3 week olds and I immediately said yes because Tango could use some friends his size. I saw how sick they were and brought them to her place where we got a positive panleuk test. Neither of us knew of anyone currently available who could take panleuk babies. So now they’re here. Satori and Bodhi are both out of the woods but still being quarantined because they may still be shedding the virus. Please consider helping us with their veterinary bill. 
PayPal: shelbyskittensafehouse@gmail.com
Venmo: fosterkittenlove
There is also a fundraiser on our FB page. If you have any animal loving friends please consider sharing the post.

Update: The mom cat eagerly took on these five babies. I’m several weeks when they are weaned they may be coming back here 🥰 

Original: This morning I fell in love with not one, not two, not three, but FIVE adorable kittens. Later today I’m bringing them to another foster parent but in the meantime I’ll be snuggling them every chance I get.
Satori and Bodhi 🥹. My little panleuk survivors.
Tango is always willing to give free hand hugs. Sometimes he even throws in a love bite.

Yes, I was asked this the other day. Followed up by commentary that the entire house is basically one giant infected space that’ll kill any unvaccinated kitten that enters and won’t be safe for them for any period of time no matter what precautions I take until Bodhi and Satori are adopted. Kind of killed my mood. This all came from someone who works in vet med (not anyone I regularly work with). It’s hard to celebrate kittens recovering from panleuk when there’s so much conflicting information on when they are considered safe to be in areas that unvaccinated kittens may be in the future. Some people say to never let them be anywhere but one room the entire time while others say 14 days. This virus is absolute hell. To put things in perspective, if I had asked the emergency vet to euthanize all three kittens rather than attempt to treat them, he would not have seen that as unreasonable. Panleukopenia is a devastating virus that not only directly takes the lives of many kittens but also can indirectly take the lives of others. During the short period of time they have been here I’ve been asked for help with 2 sets (9 kittens) of bottle babies that I’ve had to scramble to find placement for so I didn’t risk them getting panleuk. Foster homes are filling up fast and when we can’t find foster homes we aren’t able to help. I’m doing my best to navigate what I need to do going forward to make sure I’m not putting any kittens at risk. Part of me feels like an idiot for taking them in the first place especially after I was asked with exasperation how I didn’t have them euthanized upon diagnosis. I don’t regret it but this is rough.

Please help us help this sweet boy. His name is Moo. He wanted to be in my hand the entire drive to the emergency vet. He is currently requiring constant 24 hour attention and care which is something no one person should be expected to do. @theswiftiekittens kept him going all night but now he needs to be here. Hopefully we can get him back on track. I’m currently sitting in the waiting area waiting for the vet to tell me what she’d like to do.

I am blown away by your support of baby Moo. Seriously. Blown. Away. Thank you all for caring about this little underdog. Moo is approximately 7 weeks old and only weighs half a pound. He should be between 1.5 and 2 pounds right now. He’s so tiny but he’s fighting so hard. The update this morning was a good one. I got worried last night because he was having a difficult time maintaining his body temp and an even more difficult time with his blood sugar. His very attentive team made sure he was warm and given the appropriate amount of dextrose to keep him healing. He has been eating some food and they’ve been able to cut his dextrose in half. This is a big change from last night when his levels were not keeping up even when he had food. Moo is also able to maintain his body temp this morning and I feel so much better after hearing that. They are hoping to wean him off the dextrose and send him home today. As always, they’ll call if anything changes and I will update in my story. If you would like to donate to help with Moo and others like him please see my story on how to help. Donations are tax deductible. You are amazing and we are incredibly thankful for all his cheerleaders.

Please read: Unfortunately I had to take a step back from helping the cats in Salem which means Mario, Princess Peach and Yoshi will be the last kittens from there. Sometimes the hardest part of rescue is working with people. There were two instances where they backed out last minute from something we had scheduled in advance and both times it led to an emergency. Most recently (this would be the third time) they reached out and let me know the friendly mom cat is extremely ill and they don’t know what to do. They asked if I could cover the cost of her going to an emergency vet. I told them no. No because they didn’t take her to her spay appointment that was scheduled a month in advance because she changed her mind at the last second and wanted to wait “another week or two.” Honestly, I couldn’t trust they’d ever take her. Instead I reached out to NWAC and asked if they had room. They took the time to figure something out and said they could take her and her kittens. Well, the cat didn’t want to go in the carrier so she ran outside and hid. Next morning, same thing. That afternoon, same thing. Next morning, same thing. I don’t know how or why they could not block the exits of the house before trying to get her in the carrier. This poor cat is extremely ill. I kept letting NWAC know that there was a delay, another delay, and another delay. Eventually I had to tell the people in Salem that if they didn’t get her by the end of the day the rescue wouldn’t hold a spot for the cat and her kittens but that he could reach out as soon as they have the cat secured and I could ask if the rescue has space. That was Tuesday. It’s now Saturday. I don’t think they appreciate the amount of time we take out of our day to make arrangements for an incoming cat and kittens just for them to be unreliable. It’s painful knowing there are unaltered cats there and there will undoubtedly be kittens that need help. Their situation is not unique but there are many people asking for help who aren’t continually wasting the time of volunteers and making things difficult. Setting boundaries is hard but we can only do so much. I’m glad we got the ones we did.

Today is a big (and scary) day. Brie went in to be spayed with Otter and Cece. She has a suspected nasopharyngeal polyp that’s been causing her extremely noisy breathing so they’ll take a look while she’s sedated and remove it. I’m really hoping it’s a polyp and that she’ll come home later today with the ability to breathe like a normal kitten. Post meal baths next to the heater😸. Making a post about Princess Peach’s eye is going to take more effort than I expected so I can get her all the pics of her eye from when she was 3 weeks old up to now but I will be posting soon. Good news is that the news is good😁.

I’ll start with the important stuff first. Don’t laugh at my half decorated tree. She’s doing her best to stay upright with 9 kittens around. 
Thanks to our generous donors Princess Peach was able to see an ophthalmologist so we could get a thorough assessment of her eye. The damage is the result of a viral infection she had as a tiny kitten. She can still see out of the eye and the damage is only surface level. It’s not painful and doesn’t bother her so she got the all clear from the doctor. After reviewing some photos of Peach’s eye as a kitten (she had what looked like a blood blister on part of her eye) the vet was shocked and immediately checked her eye again. She couldn’t believe she wasn’t able to see any signs on her eye in that area indicating any trauma had occurred. Peach’s eye did a fantastic job healing itself. 
I was also informed that there’s a connection between formula fed kittens and cataracts. Peach has one in her good eye. When the vet noticed it she asked if Peach had been formula fed. Looking into this more. Thankfully, the cataracts don’t get worse, don’t require surgery and cause minimal, if any, vision problems.
Now that Brie’s breathing trouble is resolved she’s looking for her forever family❤️
